This article serves as a gentle introduction to Wireshark for Lab 5. Network-traffic-analysis1.pcap will serve as the example file for this tutorial.

Wireshark Interface

Wireshark’s main interface is divided into three primary panes:

  1. Packet List Pane (Top Pane): Displays a summary of each captured packet — including packet number, timestamp, source, destination, protocol, length, and info. Each line represents one packet. When you click on a packet here, the other panes show details about it. 
  2. Packet Details Pane (Middle Pane or Left Pane): Shows the decoded, hierarchical breakdown of the selected packet. You can expand protocol layers (Ethernet, IP, TCP, HTTP, etc.) to see specific fields and values. 
  3. Packet Bytes Pane (Bottom Pane or Right Pane): Displays the raw data of the selected packet in hexadecimal and ASCII format. Highlighting a field in the middle pane also highlights the corresponding bytes here.

Q1. How to find the MAC address of a client? 

  1. In the Display Filter bar type: ip.addr == 192.168.2.147
  2. Click any packet in the Packet List pane that involves that IP
  3. In the Packet Details pane expand Ethernet II. The Source and Destination fields show MAC addresses. If the packet is from the Windows client, the Source is its MAC; if it’s to the client, the Destination is its MAC.

Q2. How to find the host name for a client?

There are two methods that you can follow.

Method 1:

  1. In the Display Filter bar type: bootp
  2. Look for a DHCP Request or DHCP Inform packet from the client’s IP (for example, 192.168.2.147)
  3. Click the packet, then in the Packet Details pane expand: Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (Inform)
  4. Expand Option 12: Host Name — the value shown is the client’s hostname.

Method 2:

  1. Open Edit → Preferences → Appearance → Columns, click Add (+), and configure the new column with the following settings: Title: CNameString, Type: Custom, Fields: kerberos.CNameString. Click Apply and OK to save;
  2. In the display filter bar, enter kerberos.CNameString to show Kerberos packets containing the client name string field. In Active Directory environments, note that hostnames (machine accounts) end with a $, while user accounts do not.
  3. To display only host names, use the following filter: kerberos.CNameString and (kerberos.CNameString contains '$')

Q3. How to find the user account name of a client?

  1. Open Edit → Preferences → Appearance → Columns, click Add (+), and configure the new column with the following settings: Title: CNameString, Type: Custom, Fields: kerberos.CNameString. Click Apply and OK to save;
  2. In the display filter bar, enter kerberos.CNameString to show Kerberos packets containing the client name string field. In Active Directory environments, note that hostnames (machine accounts) end with a $, while user accounts do not.
  3. To display only user account names, use the following filter: kerberos.CNameString and !(kerberos.CNameString contains '$')

Q4. How to find the URL that returned an executable file/jpg file/png file?

  1. Open Edit → Preferences → Appearance → Columns, click Add (+), and configure the new column with the following settings: Title: Media, Type: Custom, Fields: media. Click Apply and OK to save;
  2. In the Display Filter bar type: http
  3. Look for a packet with media label ‘✓’ and click this packet;
  4. In the Packet Details pane expand: Hypertext Transfer Protocol; the Request URL and Full Request URL show the URL we are looking for.

Q5. How to find the date and time when a URL happen?

  • Follow Q4, in the Packet Details pane expand: Hypertext Transfer Protocol
  • Date and Time are listed, see the figure in Q4.

Q6. How to find the size (bytes) of a returned executable file/jpg file/png file?

  • Follow Q4, in the Packet Details pane expand: Media Type
  • Content Length and File Data also represent the size of the file, see the figure in Q4.

Q7. How to filter out TCP connection?

  1. Find the HTTP response that delivered the .exe file in Q4; Note the frame number and time;
  2. Apply this filter to see all new TCP connections after that moment: tcp.flags.syn == 1 && ip.src == 192.168.2.147
  3. This shows all outgoing TCP SYN packets (connection attempts) initiated by the infected host. Check the Time column and ensure the first SYN packet is after the frame number/time of the .exe file response.
  4. Click that SYN packet, in the Packet Details pane expand: Internet Protocol Version 4. Note the Destination address — that’s the IP the host tried to connect to after infection.
